Customer Personality Analysis¶

Life cycle of the Project¶

  1. Problem Statement

  2. Data Collection

  3. Data Cleaning

  4. Exploratory data analysis

  5. Data Pre-Processing

  6. Model Training

  7. Choose best model

  8. Recommendations

1) Problem Statement¶

  • Summarize customer segments by performing clustering

2) Data Collection¶

  • Data source: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/imakash3011/customer-personality-analysis
  • Data consists of 29 attributes -including the ID column- and 2240 samples.

Observations:

  1. Income attribute has missing value. (Type of missing data: Missing At Random)

    Will be handeled using Multivariate imputer. We will use the numerical features to impute the null values in the income feature. (Supervised learning technique). Why? because the missing values of the feature are of type (missing at random) and has outliers.

  2. Three categorical attributes (object) needs numeric encoding.

Will be handeled using hot-encoding

Table showing imputation methods for the types of missing data:

In [6]:
from sklearn.experimental import enable_iterative_imputer  
from sklearn.impute import IterativeImputer
from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingRegressor

Iterative imputation using gradient boosting regressor

In [7]:
dataset_to_impute = dataset[[col for col in dataset.columns if dataset[col].dtype != object]]
dataset_to_impute.drop(columns='Year_Birth', inplace= True)
In [8]:
sns.displot(dataset['Income'])
Out[8]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x7f810acfa1c0>
  • Because the income feature has outliers, we need an algorithm that does not get affected by outliers. Mainly tree algorithms.
  • In this case, we will use Gradient boosing regressor as our model. GBR has Decision Trees as the fixed base estimator.
In [10]:
imp = IterativeImputer(estimator = GradientBoostingRegressor())

imputed_data = imp.fit_transform(dataset_to_impute)

imputed_data = pd.DataFrame(imputed_data, columns = dataset_to_impute.columns)

print('The null values count of the Income feature after imputation is: ', imputed_data['Income'].isnull().sum())

The null values count of the Income feature after imputation is:  0

Feature Engineering¶

In [22]:
clean_dataset['Dt_Customer']
clean_dataset["Dt_Customer"] = pd.to_datetime(clean_dataset["Dt_Customer"])

Observations:

  1. We will extract one feature from the attribute ['Dt Customer']

    The feature will contain the number of days since the join of each customer from today. Feature will be called [' DaysJoin '], Days since 2015.

(why 2015?)\ Becuase the dataset is quite old. We will do our analysis from this point going forward till the latest year in the dataset, 2015. This includes the age of the customers. (will be discussed later on)

In [24]:
daysjoin = []
for date in dates:
    daysjoin.append(max(dates) - date)
    
clean_dataset['DaysJoin'] = daysjoin
clean_dataset['DaysJoin'] = pd.to_numeric(clean_dataset['DaysJoin'].dt.days, downcast='integer')
clean_dataset.drop(columns=['Dt_Customer'], inplace= True)

Observations:

  1. The first table depicts the amount spent in various products.

    We will engineer these features into 1 feature called TotalSpent

  2. The second table depicts the number of kids and teens each customer have.

    We will engineer these features into 1 feature called childern

  3. The third table depicts the year of birth of each customer.

    It is best to have this feature as the Age feature of each customer. Because the dataset is old (max year is 2015), we will only consider the age until 2015. Considering the age from today will lead to baised analysis because affliated information on these years is not available.

In [26]:
clean_dataset['TotalSpent'] = clean_dataset['MntDrinks']+ clean_dataset['MntFruits']+ clean_dataset['MntMeatProducts']+ clean_dataset['MntFishProducts']\
                          + clean_dataset['MntSweetProducts'] + clean_dataset['NumDealsPurchases']+clean_dataset['MntGoldProds']

clean_dataset['Children'] = clean_dataset['Kidhome'] + clean_dataset['Teenhome']

clean_dataset['Age'] = 2015 - clean_dataset['Year_Birth']  #As discussed earlier

We will Also add four features

  1. TotalMembers: number of members
  2. TotalPurchase: Number of purchases
  3. Parent: if the customer is a parent
  4. TotalAcceptedCamps: number of accepted camps per customer.

This will help us greatly in clustering because these features affect the shopping behavior.

In [27]:
clean_dataset['TotalMembers'] = clean_dataset['Children'] + clean_dataset['Marital_Status'].replace({'Together': 2, 'Alone': 1})
clean_dataset['Parent'] = np.where(clean_dataset['TotalMembers'] > 2, 1, 0) #For visualization
clean_dataset['TotalPurchase'] = clean_dataset['NumWebPurchases'] + clean_dataset['NumCatalogPurchases'] + clean_dataset['NumStorePurchases'] + clean_dataset['NumDealsPurchases']
clean_dataset['TotalAcceptedCamps'] = clean_dataset['AcceptedCmp1'] + clean_dataset['AcceptedCmp2'] + clean_dataset['AcceptedCmp3']+ clean_dataset['AcceptedCmp4'] + clean_dataset['AcceptedCmp5']

Lastly we will check if there are any outliers in the dataset

                   NumWebVisitsMonth  NumWebPurchases
NumWebVisitsMonth           1.000000        -0.055846

  • Both groups record the same amount of visits last month on the website.
  • Customers who buy from the website are not frequent customers. They might buy for 2-3 months forward.
  • Customers who buy little from the website tend to be frequent monthly active customers.
  • We have spectator customers who just surf the website and never buys...
  • We can see that there is a negative correlation (-0.056) between number of website visits last month and the number of web purchases. The company needs investigate what happend last month and bringforth some innovative solutions regarding their online marketing strategy.

  • Customers who spend the most tend to not accept any campaign offer the most.

Conclusion:

  1. Customers who relatively older, graduated, and have high income tend to spend the most.
  2. Drinks and Meat products generate most of the profit.
  3. Deals purchases are the lowest among all. This category is exploited by parents only. Because customers who are not parents spend the most in general, the company needs to investigate their marketing strategy on deals as it only draws parent more.
  4. For online purchases, we saw that there is no correlation between website visits last month and purchases. Therefore, the company should make online deals on a daily basis to attract customers.

This concludes exploratory data analysis

5) Data Preproceesing¶

  • We will drop features that were used to generate new, meaningful features.
  • We will drop features that do not include 2 years information (NumWebVisitsMonth).
  • Label encode categorical variables, and scale it using standardization.
  • We will drop very low variance features if they do not contribute much to the variation of data.

       v = (statistics.variance(pre_dataset[feature]))
       variance[feature] = v

low_variance_features = []

for  key ,value in variance.items():
    if value <= 0.6:
        low_variance_features.append(key)

print('Features that have low variance: ',low_variance_features)

Features that have low variance:  ['Education', 'Marital_Status', 'Children', 'Parent', 'TotalAcceptedCamps']

Clusters Profile¶

Cluster 0:

  1. Middle class payers
  2. Have at most 2 children at home.
  3. Family size does not exceed 4 members
  4. Age between 25 and 70.
  5. Amongst the cluster, customers who are parent spend a little more.
  6. Customers are graduate and postgraduate only.
  7. Moderate spendings, moderate to high incomes.

Cluster 1:

  1. High class payers.
  2. Have at most 1 child at home. Mostly a teen.
  3. Family size does not exceed 3 members
  4. Age between 25 and 75.
  5. Amongst the cluster, customers who are not parent spend the most.
  6. Customers are graduate and postgraduate only.
  7. High spendings, moderate to high incomes.

Cluster 2:

  1. Low class payers.
  2. Have at most 3 children at home.
  3. Family size reaches 5 members.
  4. Age between 19 and 75.
  5. Amongst the cluster, customers who are parent spend a little more.
  6. The only cluster that include undergraduate customers.
  7. low income, low spendings.
